[This report does not mention if Sin Nombre virus was laboratory confirmed in this case, but this virus is most likely the one responsible for this HPS case. This report is another reminder that cleaning in closed buildings that have been little used or unused over winter often provide habitats for deer mice and become sites for human exposure to Sin Nombre virus when dust is raised during cleaning. Although Sin Nombre virus infections with hantavirus pulmonary syndrome are relatively rare, the risk of death is significant.

A US Centers for Disease Control and Prevention (CDC) site with extensive information about hantaviruses, including those in North America, with clinical signs, treatment, epidemiology, and an image of the deer mouse, _Peromyscus maniculatus_, can be accessed at http://www.cdc.gov/ncidod/diseases/hanta/hps/.

The deer mouse is one of the most common and widely distributed mammals in North America and occurs in Saskatchewan. A map showing its distribution can be accessed at http://www.discoverlife.org/nh/tx/Vertebrata/Mammalia/Muridae/Peromyscus/maniculatus/images/Peromyscus_maniculatus_map.mx.jpg. An image of the deer mouse, _P. maniculatus_, can be seen at the source URL above.

A map showing the location of Saskatchewan can be accessed at http://www.sasksearch.com/travel/sask.htm and the HealthMap/ProMED-mail map at https://promedmail.org/promed-post?place=3435499,262. - Mod.TY]
